svg.title: Categorical Statements
svg.desc: A dynamic visual (using a Venn diagram) introduction to the four kinds of categorical statements of Aristotelian (traditional syllogistic) logic.

cc:Work.dc:title: Categorical Statements
cc:Work.dc:description: A dynamic visual (using a Venn diagram) introduction to the four kinds of categorical statements of Aristotelian (traditional syllogistic) logic.

text.desc: A categorical statement specifies the membership relationship between two classes of objects.
text.title: Categorical Statements

g.desc: Two intersecting circles, S and P.
g.title: Two Intersecting Circles

rect.desc: All members of the S class are members of the P class.
rect.title: A Statement

g.desc: Vertical lines shade the region of the S circle outside of the P circle, indicating nothing exists in that part of S.
g.title: Vertical Lines

rect.desc: No members of the S class belong to the P class.
rect.title: E Statement

text.tspan: the part of S that is

g.desc: Horizontal lines shading the region of intersection indicate that nothing exists that is both an S and a P.
g.title: Horizontal Lines

rect.desc: Some (at least one) member of the S class is a member of the P class.
rect.title: I Statement

path.desc: An 'X' in the region of intersection, indicating that there exists at least one S that is also a P.
path.title: X for exists

text.tspan: there exists an S that is

rect.desc: At least one member of the S class is not a member of the P class.
rect.title: O Statement

path.desc: An 'X' n the region of the S circle that is outside of the P circle; thus, an S that is not a P.
path.title: X for exists

text.tspan: S that is not a P.
